    <node id="HOME IS WHERE YOU LEFT IT&#10; &#10;&#10; By ADAM CHASE&#10; &#10; &#10; [Transcriber Note: This etext was produced from Amazing Stories February&#10;1957. Extensive research did not uncover any evidence that the U.S.&#10; copyright on this publication was renewed.]&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; The chance of mass slaughter was their eternal nightmare.&#10; &#10;&#10;&#10; How black is the blackest treachery? Is the most callous&#10; traitor entitled to mercy? Steve pondered these questions. His decision?&#10; That at times the villain should possibly be spoken of as a hero.&#10; &#10; &#10; Only the shells of deserted mud-brick houses greeted Steve Cantwell when&#10; he reached the village.&#10; &#10; He poked around in them for a while. The desert heat was searing,&#10; parching, and the Sirian sun gleamed balefully off the blades of Steve's&#10; unicopter, which had brought him from Oasis City, almost five hundred&#10; miles away. He had remembered heat from his childhood here on Sirius'&#10; second planet with the Earth colony, but not heat like this. It was like&#10; a magnet drawing all the moisture out of his body.&#10; &#10; He walked among the buildings" />
    <node id="1. Steve is determined to go after the fleeing colonists despite the danger and the old man's warning because they are his people and he feels a sense of responsibility towards them, having been away for too long. He also wants to use his &quot;extra strong right arm&quot; to help them in their journey to Oasis City or face the dangers together.&#10;2. When the old man says he has no room with the Earth folks or the Kumaji, he means that he is not welcome to return to the colony on Earth and he cannot stay with the Kumaji tribe because they will kill him for being a renegade. He has lived a good life and has no regrets, choosing to stay behind in the desert village to face death instead of fleeing with the colonists." />
    <node id="Based on the story, it is strongly implied that Tobias Whiting betrayed the caravan to the Kumaji and left in Steve's unicopter (helicopter) without saying goodbye to Mary because he had struck a deal with the Kumaji to trade the location of the Earthmen's valuable resource (presumably water or some other essential resource) for sparing his life and ensuring the safety of his daughter. However, Whiting wanted to make sure that he was revealing the information to the right people before fully committing to the deal.&#10;&#10;Whiting's intention was to deceive the Kumaji into believing that the Earthmen were heading in a different direction than where they actually were, giving them a chance to escape and avoid capture. However, it is unclear whether Whiting made it to the Kumaji encampment or not, as he disappeared during the fourth night of their journey in the desert.&#10;&#10;It's worth noting that there is some debate among the characters in the story about why Whiting left. Jeremy Gort, a friend of Whiting's and former mayor of the colony, suggests that Whiting left to try and reclaim his lost fortune with the Kumaji, and that he may have crash-landed or crashed in the desert trying to reach them. However, this theory is unlikely given the evidence presented in the story.&#10;&#10;Overall, while the story does not provide a definitive answer as to why Whiting left in Cantwell's helicopter without saying goodbye to Mary, it strongly implies that he did so as part of a betrayal to the Kumaji in order to trade information about the Earthmen's valuable resource for his life and safety." />
