ey are his people and he feels a sense of responsibility towards them, having been away for too long. He also wants to use his &quot;extra strong right arm&quot; to help them in their journey to Oasis City or face the dangers together.&#10;5. The story does not provide explicit information about who poisoned the well or why. However, based on the context and the fact that the Kumaji tribesmen had never accepted the colony as a fact of their life on the desert, it is strongly implied that they are responsible for poisoning the well. This action was likely taken in an effort to drive out the Earth colony, which had settled in the oasis and was using up resources that the Kumaji also relied on for their own survival. The poisoning of the well ultimately led to the desertion of the town and Steve's delayed return to his boyhood home from Earth.&#10;6. When faced with the threat of torture by the Kumajis, Steve considers silencing Tobias Whiting to prevent him from revealing any information. However, he ultimately decides against it because he knows that the Kumajis have one willing prisoner and two unwilling ones, and if Whiting yells for help but the yelling is kept to a minimum, only one guard would come to investigate. This would allow Steve to overpower the guard and escape with Mary.">
